{"title": "Possible HTTP verb confusion", "summary": " Rails uses the same actions for both GET and HEAD requests. When creating actions that handle both GET and state altering verbs (eg. POST), the use of `request.get?` can lead to unexpected state changes.  ### Remediations  \u2705 Use separate action logic for GET and POST  \u2705 Check for state altering verbs rather than GET:  ```ruby if request.post?   alter_state end ``` ", "description": "\nRails uses the same actions for both GET and HEAD requests. When creating\nactions that handle both GET and state altering verbs (eg. POST), the use\nof `request.get?` can lead to unexpected state changes.\n\n### Remediations\n\n\u2705 Use separate action logic for GET and POST\n\n\u2705 Check for state altering verbs rather than GET:\n\n```ruby\nif request.post?\n  alter_state\nend\n```\n", "recommendations": "", "taxonomy": ["CWE-650"], "references": ["https://docs.bearer.com/reference/rules/ruby_rails_http_verb_confusion"], "details": "{% include '../generic_bandit_issue/details' %}"}